      "date": "2016-08-13T16:50:53-04:00",
      "modified": "2016-10-03T23:19:23-04:00",
      "title": "No, Kevin Roberts. Gender Diversity is Still a Problem.",
      "URL": "https://rainesinternational.wordpress.com/2016/08/13/publicis-kevin-roberts-comments-diversity-matter/",
      "short_URL": "http://wp.me/p7C5yw-26l",
      "content": "<hr />\n<p>At Raines International, we constantly and consistently advocate for diversity and inclusion. Diversity efforts are well-documented as boosting the bottom line, staff morale, and creativity &amp; innovation. Despite these visible benefits, a lot of work <a href=\"http://consultanttrack.com/reading-july-8/#.V6aH4-grKDs\">needs to be done</a> to balance gender and racial diversity in the advertising world.</p>\n<p>Publicis Groupe executive and Saatchi &amp; Saatchi Chairman Kevin Roberts got into hot water this week when he <a href=\"http://www.businessinsider.com/kevin-roberts-on-women-in-leadership-roles-2016-7\">told Business Insider</a> he doesn&#8217;t think there are any gender diversity problems in advertising and hence doesn&#8217;t spend &#8220;any time&#8221; on gender-related issues within his companies.</p>\n<p>When looking to make sense of the lack of female representation in the industry, Roberts suggested that women don&#8217;t want to be in the C-suite and instead just want to be happy. &#8220;Their ambition is not a vertical ambition,&#8221; he explains. &#8220;It&#8217;s this intrinsic, circular ambition to be happy.&#8221;</p>\n<p>Roberts continued, &#8220;I don&#8217;t think [the lack of women in leadership roles] is a problem. I&#8217;m just not worried about it because they are very happy, they&#8217;re very successful and doing great work. I can&#8217;t talk about sexual discrimination because we&#8217;ve never had that problem, thank goodness.&#8221;</p>\n<p>Roberts isn&#8217;t alone in his assumptions. The advertising industry needs to take serious steps to increase diversity because right now it&#8217;s flunking the diversity test. “I don’t think we’re in a good place at all,” Carolyn Everson, <a class=\"company-name\" href=\"http://quotes.wsj.com/FB\">Facebook</a>’s Vice President of Global Marketing Solutions, told the Wall Street Journal earlier this year at the American Association of Advertising Agencies&#8217;s Conference in Miami.</p>\n<p>Supporting Carolyn&#8217;s claim, the Bureau of Labor Statistics’ Current Population Survey <a href=\"http://www.wsj.com/articles/why-the-picture-of-diversity-on-madison-avenue-is-so-murky-1458332278\">found</a> paltry diversity numbers in the composition of the advertising and public relations industries, let alone in the top executive roles:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>49% Women</li>\n<li>5.3% African American</li>\n<li>11.7% Hispanics</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Rounding out these bits of incriminating evidence, J. Walter Thompson (the fourth-largest ad agency in the world) CEO Gustvao Martinez <a href=\"http://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-in-advertising-sparks-heated-discussions-at-industry-conference-1458747430\">resigned</a> earlier this year after being accused of racism and sexism. While Martinez denied the claims, he and J. Walter Thompson were sued for an “unending stream of racist and sexist comments as well as unwanted touching and other unlawful conduct.”</p>\n<p>Roberts&#8217; feelings aren&#8217;t shared by Saatchi &amp; Saatchi and Publicis, however. Shortly after his comments went public, he was put on leave July 31, and the company emphasized its commitment to diversity and inclusion. (Just a few days later, Roberts took himself out of the picture and <a href=\"http://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/04/business/media/publicis-executive-kevin-roberts-is-out-after-gender-diversity-remarks.html?_r=0\">told</a> the New York Times he is leaving Publicis Sept. 1. Roberts said he miscommunicated and apologized.)</p>\n<p>&#8220;Diversity and inclusion are business imperatives on which Publicis Groupe will not negotiate,&#8221; Publicis said in a statement. &#8220;While fostering a work environment that is inclusive of all talent is a collective responsibility, it is leadership’s job to nurture the career aspirations and goals of all our talent.&#8221;</p>\n<p>Publicis doubled down, saying it believes &#8220;promoting gender equality starts at the top.&#8221;</p>\n<p>&#8220;Publicis Groupe works very hard to champion diversity and will continue to insist that each agency’s leadership be champions of both diversity and inclusion,&#8221; the statement ends. We can only hope that other companies will soon begin to do the same.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
      "excerpt": "<p>Diversity efforts are well-documented as boosting the bottom line, staff morale, and creativity and innovation. Despite these visible benefits, a lot of work needs to be done to balance gender and racial diversity in the advertising world.</p>\n",
