      "date": "2016-07-29T13:38:03+00:00",
      "modified": "2016-10-07T09:26:50-04:00",
      "title": "Why It&#8217;s a Good Time to Be a Consultant",
      "URL": "https://rainesinternational.wordpress.com/2016/07/29/good-time-consultant/",
      "short_URL": "http://wp.me/p7C5yw-25L",
      "content": "<hr />\n<p>It&#8217;s a good time to be a consultant in the United States &#8212; the consulting market is booming.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.wsj.com/articles/cfos-turn-to-consultants-as-challenges-mount-1469468219\">According</a> to the Wall Street Journal&#8217;s Tatyana Shumsky, more and more U.S. corporations &#8212; Chief Financial Officers specifically &#8212; are hiring outside consultants to help grow revenue and tackle the increasingly complex set of problems and opportunities facing companies today.</p>\n<p>And the statistics back it up.  Market research firm Source Global Research, which focuses on large and midsize consultants, found that the U.S. consulting market is now a $55 billion industry.</p>\n<p>&#8220;The U.S. consulting market, the world&#8217;s largest, grew by $3.9 billion, or 7.7%, in 2015 to $54.7 billion, according to Source Global Research,&#8221; the Wall Street Journal reported. But that&#8217;s not it. Source Global Research projects a 10% increase in 2016.</p>\n<p>To what is the growth attributed? Fast-paced technological innovation, increased regulation and new competition are among the factors, according to consultants and market researchers.</p>\n<p>That said, there&#8217;s a fine line between using consultants to do work executives should know how to and having consultants supplement executive actions.  AlixPartners LLP&#8217;s Senior Vice Chairman Fred Crawford suggests the best time for consultants is when a company requires &#8220;a surge of qualified, capable people that you need for a period of time but not forever.&#8221;</p>\n<p>Executive search firm Raines International, however, says otherwise. The New York-based firm is witnessing a growing trend of hiring consultants across industries and functions, highlighting the growing importance of securing a consulting background in their leadership teams. In 2015, the company experienced a 15% increase in the number of consultants it placed in industry roles over the last five years. In addition, an increasingly large set of the firm&#8217;s clients specifically request hiring individuals with a management consulting background.</p>\n<p>“We’ve seen a large expansion in the functional breadth of client needs with regards to current or former consultant talent,&#8221; said Alison Hunter, a Core Member of Raines&#8217; Strategy Practice.</p>\n<blockquote><p>&#8220;With Raines’ long-standing and extensive work with the consulting community, we have certainly witnessed a growing variety in the ways a current or former consultant can make an impact in an organization than there was previously. From top finance jobs to transformative human resources roles, our clients are increasingly looking for individuals with a strong skillset from an external consulting firm to lead innovation and to drive change and growth within many different areas of a company. ”</p></blockquote>\n<p>The growth of the consulting industry over the past year signals the increasing value leaders across industries place on the management consulting acumen. While many still see consultants as a temporary fix to their business concerns, the increasingly complex set of obstacles and opportunities business leaders face today are leading many to hire consultants as permanent members of their leadership teams. In any case, it sure is a good time to be a consultant.</p>\n<p>Check out the <a href=\"http://www.sourceglobalresearch.com/report/download/1284/extract/0/The-US-Consulting-Market\">extract for the Source Global Research report.</a></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n",
      "excerpt": "<p>It&#8217;s a good time to be a consultant in the United States &#8212; the consulting market is booming.</p>\n",
